From: Julius Bairaktaris <julius@bairaktaris.de>
Subject: [PATCH] mac80211: allocate per-CPU transmit queues for NSS offload

The NSS offload data path bypasses the mac80211 TXQs entirely: every
frame goes through dev_queue_xmit and the transmit-queue lock of its
netdev queue straight into the NSS virtual-device redirect. mac80211
allocates interface netdevs with a single transmit queue (the TXQ
world has no use for more), so all concurrent senders serialize on one
xmit lock - measured as a ~1 Gbit/s ceiling for locally sourced
transmit towards an HE160 station on IPQ8074, with the radio idle a
quarter of the time and no CPU saturated.

Allocate one transmit queue per CPU on NSS-enabled builds. Neither
data netdev_ops implements ndo_select_queue, so the core flow-hashes
traffic across the queues (per-flow ordering is preserved), and the
mac80211 queue wake/stop machinery operates on the internal TXQs
without ever touching netdev subqueues, so host-mode operation is
unaffected.

Signed-off-by: Julius Bairaktaris <julius@bairaktaris.de>
--- a/net/mac80211/iface.c
+++ b/net/mac80211/iface.c
@@ -2228,9 +2228,28 @@ int ieee80211_if_add(struct ieee80211_lo
 			txq_size += sizeof(struct txq_info) +
 				    local->hw.txq_data_size;
 
+#ifdef CPTCFG_MAC80211_NSS_SUPPORT
+		/*
+		 * The NSS offload data path bypasses the mac80211 TXQs:
+		 * every frame takes the netdev transmit-queue lock straight
+		 * into the NSS virtual-device redirect, so with the single
+		 * default queue all sender threads serialize on one lock
+		 * (measured ceiling ~1 Gbit/s for locally sourced transmit
+		 * on IPQ8074). Give the interface one transmit queue per
+		 * CPU: neither data netdev_ops implements ndo_select_queue,
+		 * so the core flow-hashes across the queues, and the
+		 * wake_tx_queue world never touches netdev subqueues, so
+		 * the extra queues are invisible to the host-mode path.
+		 */
+		ndev = alloc_netdev_mqs(size + txq_size,
+					name, name_assign_type,
+					ieee80211_if_setup,
+					num_possible_cpus(), 1);
+#else
 		ndev = alloc_netdev_mqs(size + txq_size,
 					name, name_assign_type,
 					ieee80211_if_setup, 1, 1);
+#endif
 		if (!ndev)
 			return -ENOMEM;
 
